s as they are all legends in their fields and so down-to-earth and yet we all shoot weddings. I think that''s so cool.\n\nIf you asked me a year ago who I would like to work with in the future then I wouldn''t have been able to name any of the names I just mentioned. I don''t really have a list of who''s who that I want to work with. It''s often the unknowns that are so fun &amp; inspiring to work with moreso than the big personalities.\n<div class="line-style-2"></div>\n<blockquote class="full-width">“ It’s amazing what you begin to see when you start looking. Particularly in a city like this.”</blockquote>\n<div class="line-style-2"></div>\n<div><img class="right" src="http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-audi.jpeg" alt="" width="640" height="427" /></div>\n<div class="caption right">Image caption information image caption</div>\n<h3 class="question">Asher:</h3>\nWhat is your current set up and what''s on the wish list?\n<h3 class="answer clear-left">Glen:</h3>\nHere''s the list:\n\n- 5DmkII\n- 5D (the original - still use this guy cos the colour is just awesome on skin tones. ask any professional photo editor. And the feel of the shutter is this awesome old school ''clunk''.)\n- 85mm f1.2 (the fave)\n- 50mm f1.2\n- 24-70mm f2.8\n- 70-200mm f2.8 II ("the sniper"... far out this guy is so heavy)\n\n...and then a few flashes and bits and pieces you know, all in my (now heavy) Billingham 550.\nI also shoot 35mm film on a Leica Minilux and an ancient beaten up Canon A2.\n\nOn the wish list is for Canon to bring out a 35mm f1.2. The 35mm 1.4 is beautiful, but f1.2 is f1.2 and I have this inkling that the moment I buy the f1.4 they''ll announce the 1.2 and I''ll be instantly jealous. A lot of readers may not understand that sentence, sorry. Ha. Whilst we''re on the wish list wagon I''d throw in a Leica Noctilux 50mm f0.95 (the quickest way to spend $11K) and a Leica M7. Please.\n<h3 class="question">Asher:</h3>\nDo you have any advice to give fellow photographers looking to expand their client base?\n<h3 class="answer">Glen:</h3>\nWell... I just think if you do a great job and over-deliver then there''s a better chance you''ll get a referral. And from referrals come more referrals and so on. Be nice. Don''t burn people. Be yourself (unless of course you normally burn people in which case don''t be yourself, just be someone nice).\n<h3 class="question">Asher:</h3>\nWhat are some of your favourite locations to shoot?\n<h3 class="answer">Glen:</h3>\nI''ve had some amazing opportunities particularly since working for Christian. The first week I got here Christian sat me down and asked if I was ok to go shoot a wedding in Switzerland in 2 weeks time ("umm yes"). That was epic. Besides that we shot a wedding party that went rafting in Jackson Hole Wyoming, an on-stage wedding in a massive old theatre in Texas, a bushfire-smoke-filled few days in Georgia amongst the hanging mossy trees, sunset on the beach in the Hamptons, a lobster picnic dinner for 250 guests in Martha''s Vineyard... yeah we''ve seen some amazing stuff.\n\nOne of my old favourites though is a little place right on the water in Palm Beach, Sydney, called "The Boathouse". Sea planes come in and out, the food is perfectly Australian, the atmosphere super relaxed, the sunset is so peaceful and the staff are way too nice to call them ''staff''. I used to shoot a lot there and that''s one of the locations I miss the most in Sydney.\n\n<img class="full-width" src="http://iandi.spiraldesign.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/glenallsop-fullwidth-image2.jpg" alt="" />\n<div class="caption right">Image caption information image caption\ninformation</div>\n<h3 class="question clear-left">Asher:</h3>\nWhat are some of the best things about being a photographer?\n<h3 class="answer">Glen:</h3>\nShooting. I just love shooting. Some days I love it because of the people I meet, some days its the opportunity to shoot something ridiculously amazing, other days I just like the feel of the shutter under my finger, other days its the delayed gratification of not knowing what the picture''s going to look like until I take another 35 shots to finish the roll and then get it developed. I love it all and wouldn''t trade it for anything.', 'GLEN ALLSOP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '72-autosave', '', '', '2012-03-19 14:40:33', '2012-03-19 21:40:33', '', 72, 'http://spiraldesign.ca/72-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
